Part 1: One-Liners

One of the most common and clever BASH scripting techniques is the one-liner. A one-liner is a string of Linux commands separated by a semicolon or a pipe that does something useful. In this first set of tasks, you will learn some cool one-liners.

  1. From the dock at the bottom of the screen, click the Terminal icon to open a new terminal window.
  2. At the command prompt, execute ls -la | grep -v '^d' | wc -l and press Enter to count the files in the current directory.

    One of the best ways to understand a piped command is to execute each piped section in order:
         ls -la
    la -la | grep -v '^d'
    la -la | grep -v '^d' | wc -l
    The command breaks down as follows:

         ls -la - Print all files and directories (including hidden flies) to the screen.
         grep -v '^d' - Search for things that do not (-v) start (^) with lowercase "d".
         wc -l - Count each line (-l).

         Note: This one-liner takes advantage of the fact that directory listings start with lower-case "d" for directory.
  3. What if you only wanted to count directories and not files? Simply remove the -v in the grep statement:
         ls -la | grep '^d' | wc -l
  4. Execute find . -maxdepth 1 -type f to find all files in the current directory.

    The find command is     recursive, so we use -maxdepth 1 to limit the results to the current directory only.

         Note: To find directories use find . -maxdepth 1 -type d
  5. What if we wanted to know how large these files are? Execute the command below:
         find . -maxdepth 1 -type f -exec du -h {} \;
    The     du command stands for disk usage, and -h makes the results human readable.

         Note: You might have thought to try piping find into the  du command:
         find . -maxdepth 1 -type f | du -h
    Feel free to try this, but it does not work. Some commands cannot pipe directly into other commands. In these cases, the -         exec {} \; function works.
  6. What if we want to sort the files from largest to smallest? Execute the command to see the results. By default, sort will display items from smallest to largest. The -r reverses this.
         find . -maxdepth 1 -type f -exec du -h {} \; | sort -r
  7. What if we only want to see the five largest files? You can pipe one more time into the head command:
         find . -maxdepth 1 -type f -exec du -h {} \; | sort -r | head -5
    Let's learn a little about looping using the     for loop. For loops start with a value, set a maximum or minimum for the value, and increment or decrement the value until the maximum or minimum is reached. While looping, the for loop will repeat some task. Let's see an example.
  8. Execute for ((a=1; a<=10; a++)); do echo $a; done to print the numbers 1 through 10 on the screen.

    The for loop starts with variable         a set to 1. Next, the for loop checks to see if a is less than or equal to 10. Then a is incremented by 1. The for loop will continue to echo the value of a until it reaches 10.
  9. Could we use sort to reverse the output of a for loop? Try the following:
         for ((a=1; a<=10; a++)); do echo $a; done | sort -r
    Notice that -r does not quite do what we want. It places the 10 over the 1. That is because BASH is thinking like a computer. To fix this, add an h to the sort command so BASH sorts numbers the way a human would:
         for ((a=1; a<=10; a++)); do echo $a; done | sort -rh
  10. We can also count from 10 to 1 using:
         for ((a=10; a>=1; a--)); do echo $a; done
    Note: Notice the value of a starts at 10 and decrements down to 1.

         Brace expansion provides another way to loop. Brace expansion tells BASH to start with a first value and increment to a last value.
  11. Execute echo {1..10} to see brace expansion at work.

         Note: Could you reverse the number order using | sort -rh ? Try it! Sadly this does not work, but you can use echo {10..1}.
  12. Execute echo {a..c}{1..5} to see how brace expansion is used to create string patterns.
    Try other patterns like echo {a..c}{1..3}{x..z} or echo a{1..5}b etc. Brace expansion is fun! Can we combine brace expansion and for loops? Yes, we can!
  13. Execute for a in {1..10}; do echo $a; done

    Notice this works the same as the for loop in Step 8. Try     for a in {10..1}; do echo $a; done as well.
  14. Let's combine for loops and brace expansion to ping sweep a subnet. First, find your lab servers IP address using the ip a command.
  15. Execute for a in {1..254} ;do (ping -c 1 X.X.X.$a | grep "bytes from" &) ; done (replacing X.X.X with the first three octets of your IP address) to ping the entire subnet.
    For a massive collection of BASH one-liners, see https://www.bashoneliners.com/

Part 2: Arrays

Next, let's learn about arrays. Arrays allow us to store and retrieve strings and integers stored in contiguous memory. We reference an array item by its number in the array.

  1. Execute names=('John' 'Fred' 'Sally' 'Billy' 'Charlie') to create an array called names with five names.
  2. Execute echo ${names[0]} to print out the first name in the array.

         Note: Array items always start with zero.
  3. Execute echo ${names[1]} to print out the second name in the list.

    Here are some other cool things you can do with an array
  4. Execute echo ${names[@]} to print out everything in the array on one line.
  5. Execute echo ${!names[@]} to print out the array indices.
  6. Execute echo ${#names[@]} to print out the size of the array.

    Could we use a for loop to print all the names in the array? You could first use     ${#names[@]} to find the array's length. Then subtract one from that value as arrays start from zero.  In the case of names, ${#names[@]} = 5, so we want to loop from 0 to 4. Finally, you can use either of these for loops:
         for ((a=0; a<=4; a++)); do echo ${names[$a]}; doneor
         for a in {0..4}; do echo ${names[$a]}; done
    But there is a better way
  7. Execute for name in ${names[@]}; do echo $name; done to print out all items in the names array.

    Using this method, we dont need to know how many items are in the array. The for loop will simply keep going until it reaches the last item.
    Can we modify an array once created? Yes!
  8. Execute names[2]='Tom' to replace the third item in the array (sorry, Sally), then execute echo ${names[@]} to validate.
  9. Execute names[5]='Sally ' to add a new 6th item to the array, then execute echo ${names[@]} to validate Sally's triumphant return to the array. We missed Sally!
    Note: What if you tried names[10]='Timmy' ? If you validated using echo ${names[@]} it would look like Timmy was added directly after Sally, but in truth, array items 6-9 are blank. If you try echo ${names[6]} or 7 or 8 or 9, it will be empty. Only echo ${names[10]} will be Timmy. 

Part 3: Reusable Scripts

So far, all our scripting has been done directly in the terminal. It's time to create reusable scripts. In the next section, we will write our scripts using Text Editor. We will then execute them in the terminal, so leave it open.

  1. Right-click on the Desktop and select Create Document > Empty File. Name the file script1.sh.
  2. At line 1, type #!/bin/bash and press Enter.

    You should start all your BASH scripts with #!/bin/bash. This     shebang ensures Linux runs your script using the correct shell (BASH).

         Note: Some argue that #!/usr/bin/env bash is more universal. Our scripts will use the traditional #!/bin/bash.

    Next, you will write your script, line by line. Linux will execute each line as a command. There is no need for line termination (e.g., a semicolon). It's ok to skip a line to make the script more readable; blank lines are simply ignored. Indentation is not required, but as you will see, it makes reading a script much easier.          Spacing is crucial, so pay attention to spacing in the examples below.
  3. Enter the text below into script1.sh:
         #!/bin/bash

    greetings="Hello"
    user=$(whoami)

    echo "$greetings $user!"
    This script assigns the string "Hello" to a variable called         greetings. The whoami command is used for the user variable. Then a greeting is echoed to the screen.
  4. On the Text Editor toolbar, click Save.
  5. In the terminal window, type cd Desktop and press Enter, then type chmod +x script1.sh and press Enter to make script1.sh executable.
  6. In the terminal window, execute ./script1.sh to run the script.
  7. In the Text Editor window, modify the script as shown below. This time we use the read function to get the user's input for the user variable.
         #!/bin/bash

    greetings="Hello"
    echo "Please enter your name:"
    read user

    echo "$greetings $user!"
  8. In the Text Editor, save your changes.
  9. In the terminal window, execute ./script1.sh to re-run script1.sh with the new changes.
  10. In the Text Editor window, change the script again, as shown below. This time we create a function called greet() and pass that function the user variable.
         #!/bin/bash
    greet() {
    echo "Hello $user!"
    }

    echo "Please enter your name:"
    read user

    greet "$user"
  11. Save your changes in Text Editor, then run script1.sh in the terminal.
    The following script is a little more challenging. Lets write a fruit taster. First, we will create a text file with a list of fruits.
  12. Create a text file on the Desktop called fruits.txt.
  13. Edit the file as shown below. Be sure to save the file.

    apples
    oranges
    bananas
    kiwis
    grapes
    melons
    lemons
    berries
    Note: Do not hit Enter after berries. Doing so will make the script below fail.
  14. On the Desktop, create a new script called script2.sh and make it executable.
  15. Enter the following code into script2.sh and save it.
         #!/bin/bash

    mapfile -t fruits < "fruits.txt"

    arrayLength=${#fruits[@]}

    firstFruit=0
    lastFruit=$((arrayLength-1))

    echo "There are $arrayLength fruits in the array."
    echo "The first fruit is ${fruits[$firstFruit]}."
    echo "The last fruit is ${fruits[$lastFruit]}."
    In this script, we use the     mapfile function to create an array called fruits from the fruits.txt text file. Mapfile will read fruits.txt line by line and put each line into the fruits array.

    Next, we set the     arrayLength variable to the length of the fruits array. We create a firstFruit variable and set it to zero, as zero is always the first item in an array. Then we create a lastFruit variable and set it to arrayLength minus one.

    Finally, we echo to the screen the array length, the first item in the array, and the last item in the array.
  16. Run script2.sh in the terminal window.
    Now that we know the fruits array works as expected, let's taste some fruit!
  17. Modify script2.sh as shown below, then save it.
         #!/bin/bash

    mapfile -t fruits < "fruits.txt"

    arrayLength=${#fruits[@]}

    firstFruit=0
    lastFruit=$((arrayLength-1))

    echo "There are $arrayLength fruits in the array."
    echo "The first fruit is ${fruits[$firstFruit]}."
    echo "The last fruit is ${fruits[$lastFruit]}."

    for fruit in ${fruits[@]}
    do
      if [ $fruit != "melons" ]
      then
    echo "I love $fruit!"
      else
    echo "Yuck, $fruit."
      fi
    done
    We have added a     for loop that iterates through each array item in the fruits array. Each pass, the value of the fruit variable is compared to the string "melon". If there is no match (!=), then we love the fruit. If fruit equals melon then we say yuck.
  18. Run script2.sh in the terminal window.
    Good variable names help make a script easy to read and support. In script2.sh above, we could have written the code as shown below. This version of script2.sh works, but it is much easier to understand with well-named variables.
         #!/bin/bash

    mapfile -t x < "fruits.txt"

    a=${#x[@]}

    z=0
    r=$((a-1))

    echo "There are $a fruits in the array."
    echo "The first fruit is ${fruits[$z]}."
    echo "The last fruit is ${fruits[$r]}."

    for $q in ${x[@]}
    do
      if [ $q != "melon" ]
      then
    echo "I love $fruit!"
      else
    echo "Yuck, $fruit."
      fi
    done
         Another way to make your code more understandable is to use comments. A comment is text that is ignored when a script executes. Comments describe what a script is doing and how it works. In BASH, the # symbol is used to create a comment. Lets add some comments to our super judgy anti-melon fruit taster.
         #!/bin/bash

    #Create the fruits array from the fruits text file
    mapfile -t fruits < "fruits.txt"

    #Assign variables based on the fruits arrays length
    arrayLength=${#fruits[@]}

    firstFruit=0
    lastFruit=$((arrayLength-1))

    #Print array facts to the screen

    echo "There are $arrayLength fruits in the array."
    echo "The first fruit is ${fruits[$firstFruit]}."
    echo "The last fruit is ${fruits[$lastFruit]}."

    #Compare every fruit in the fruits array to melon
    for $fruit in ${fruits[@]}
    do
      if [ $fruit != "melon" ]
      then
    echo "I love $fruit!"
      else
    echo "Yuck, $fruit."
      fi
    done
         Note: #!/bin/bash is not a comment even though it starts with #

    As seen above, describing in detail what every line of code does is unnecessary. The person reading your code should understand BASH. However, it's good to explain what each code section is doing. Good variable names and informative comments will help make your code easy to read and support long after you have forgotten what your code does or why you wrote it.

    Now let's create a primitive backup tool using BASH!
  19. On the Desktop, create script3.sh and make it executable.
  20. Enter the following code into script3.sh and save. There is no need to type in the comments; they are there to help you understand the script.
         #!/bin/bash

    #Assign variables
    backup="script_backups"

    #Check if the script_backups directory exists, and if not create it    if [ ! -d "$backup" ]
    then
      mkdir "$backup"
    fi

    #Put directory listing of .sh files into a text file
    ls -la *.sh > scripts.txt

    #Create an array containing script names from scripts.txt
    scripts=$(cat scripts.txt | awk '{print $9}')

    #Loop through the scripts array; copy scripts to script_backups
    for script in ${scripts[@]}
    do
      echo "Copying $script to $backup"
      cp "$script" "$backup"
    done

    #Validate the contents of script_backups
    echo "Here are the contents of $backup :"
    ls -la "$backup"
  21. Run script3.sh and observe the results.
    On the Desktop, you will see a folder called script_backups containing copies of script1.sh, script2.sh and script3.sh.

    The magic behind script3.sh is a tool called     awk. Awk is a parsing tool for Linux. Lets look at how it works in our backup script above.
  22. In the terminal window, execute cat scripts.txt to view the file's contents.

    If we look at the output, we can see     nine distinct columns. The text we want for our array is in column 9.
  23. Execute cat scripts.txt | awk '{print $9}' to have awk print column 9.
  24. Execute scripts=$(cat scripts.txt | awk '{print $9}') to create an array called scripts containing the list of files (column 9) from awk.
  25. Execute echo ${scripts[@]} to see the contents of the array. Magic!

Summary

In this lab, you learned a few handy BASH one-liners. You then learned about looping and arrays. Next, you took on three simple scripts to explore looping, arrays, and if-then-else statements. You also learned about creating arrays with mapfile (for reading text files) and awk (for parsing text files).

As with any new skill, your ability to use and understand scripting will grow as you actively use BASH to solve problems. One way to grow stronger is to try your hand at CTF and other challenges that use BASH, such as: https://www.hackerrank.com/domains/shell

You are now ready for a challenge!
